data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which work identically in .NET 8. **No migration is needed.**

That said, the code could be modernized to use `Task`-based parallelism, which is idiomatic in modern .NET:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    var tasks = items.Select(item => Task.Run(() => Process(item)));
    await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
}
```

This gives you better thread pool utilization and built-in support for `CancellationToken` if you need it later.
